# Novartis dataset challenge
## Introduction and Strategy
In order to model the sensor dataset, we need to have a predictor value that is not provided. We assume that after each failure event, the machine is functioning normal because it was repaired by a technician. Therefore the basic assumption to further model the sensor dataset is to generate a "health" index for the machine that takes a low value directly after a failure event (0 = instrument 0% damaged) and a high value at the following failure date (1 = instrument 100% damaged). We assume further that instrument breakdown is a gradual process and the health index increases incremental in a linear fashion. Then, for the modeling we decide to use a linear regression model. One advantage with this model is rubustness towards overfitting, another advantage is that we can extract the coefficients (individual sensor data), that contribute most to a failure event. 

## Data import and preprocessing
First, we import all the packages that will be used for all processing, modelling and visualisation

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import networkx as nx
from scipy import stats
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
Then we read the two datasets, sensordata as df_sensor and failing events data as df_fail.
df_fail = pd.read_excel('/Users/David/Dropbox/Python3/git/Novartis_Apr19/IE01.552.051-data_pack.xlsx',sheet_name=1)
df_sensor = pd.read_excel('/Users/David/Dropbox/Python3/git/Novartis_Apr19/IE01.552.051-data_pack.xlsx',sheet_name=0)
For the failing and sensor dataset, the timestamp is created and used as index.

df_fail['Timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df_fail['FailureStartDate'] + ' ' + df_fail['FailureStartTime'], dayfirst = True)

df_fail.set_index('Timestamp', inplace=True)
df_sensor.set_index('Timestamp', inplace=True)

# Timestamp from failing data outside sensor data will be removed
df_fail = df_fail.drop(df_fail[df_fail.index < min(df_sensor.index)].index)
df_fail = df_fail.drop(df_fail[df_fail.index > max(df_sensor.index)].index)
df_fail = df_fail.sort_index()

print(df_fail.info())

We see that from 25 failing times there are 18 remaing which fall in the sensordata timeframe. In the next step, Numerical values and categorical values are identified. Also, missing values are imputed using the median of the individul column. For further modelling, categorical values are converted to dummy variables.

sensorindex = df_sensor.columns.tolist()
number_nonnas = []

for i in sensorindex:
    number_nonnas = sum(pd.to_numeric(df_sensor[i],errors='coerce').isna())
    if number_nonnas < 109009:
        df_sensor[i] = pd.to_numeric(df_sensor[i],errors='coerce')
        df_sensor[i] = df_sensor[i].fillna(df_sensor[i].median())
    else:
        df_sensor[i] = df_sensor[i].astype('category')

# Categorical values are converted to dummy variables
df_sensor = pd.get_dummies(df_sensor)
print(df_sensor.info())

Outliers (spikes) were found in some variables (not shown here). These outlier values are identified using zscore statistics and replaced with the median. Furthermore, variables are normalized by setting the baseline of the sensordata (= median) to zero and setting maximum to 1. As consequence, every sensordata receives equal weight. This is important later for the interpretation of the model coefficients.

variables_with_outliers = ['PI552051.642','PI552051.645','PI552051.651','TIC552051.616','WI552051.675']
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))

# show example sensordata before normalization
df_sensor['WI552051.675'].plot()
plt.title('WI552051.675 before cleaning')

# Identify outliers using zscore and replace using median
for i in variables_with_outliers:
    zscore = stats.zscore(df_sensor[i])
    df_sensor.loc[abs(df_sensor[i]) > 1e8,i] = np.median(df_sensor[i])
    df_sensor.loc[abs(zscore) > 10,i] = np.median(df_sensor[i])
    
# only for the float variables (not categoricals) we will apply further normalization
allfloats = df_sensor.dtypes.index[df_sensor.dtypes == float].tolist()

for i in allfloats:
    df_sensor[i] = df_sensor[i]-np.median(df_sensor[i])
    df_sensor[i] = df_sensor[i]/max(df_sensor[i])

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))

# show example data after normalization
df_sensor['WI552051.675'].plot()
plt.title('WI552051.675 after cleaning')

Data is collected every 10 minutes. As many signals show "spiking" events (see e.g. graphic above), it is a good idea to sum signals over a larger timeframe in order to reduce noise coming from spiking. In the following, we resample the data by 3-hour intervals.
df_sensor = df_sensor.resample('3H').sum()
df_sensor.head()

We now define intervals of machine runs between the different failing times. We ignore the interval before the first breakdown and the one after the last breakdown, because both don't cover the full timerange from one failure state to another. Following steps are performed:
- Each interval is indexed by introducing a "failindex" column.
- For each interval, we define a 'breakdowntime' variable. This newly created variable consists of incremental values from 0 (= First day of machine functioning after repair) to 1 (= Machine breakdown)

# New columns are created
df_sensor['failindex'] = np.zeros(len(df_sensor))
df_sensor['breakdownindex'] = np.zeros(len(df_sensor))

# for each failing event, we introduce input for both newly created variables.
for index in range(17):
    lefttime = df_sensor.index > df_fail.index[index]
    righttime = df_sensor.index < df_fail.index[index+1]
    selecttime = [lefttime[i] and righttime[i] for i in range(len(lefttime))]
    df_sensor.loc[selecttime,'failindex'] = index+1
    df_sensor.loc[selecttime,'breakdownindex'] = np.linspace(0,1,sum(selecttime))
    
# We plot the breakdown index of the last interval
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
df_sensor.loc[selecttime,'breakdownindex'].plot()
plt.ylabel('breakdownindex')

## Applying the linear regression model
Now that we defined predictor values for the sensordata, we can apply the model.
As discussed above, we use a linear regression model and apply it to the 17 time intervals between the 18 fail event.

# %% Create model on all 17 breakdown events. We select only the data with breakdownindex > 0 as they represent full intervals (fail event to next fail event)
X = df_sensor[df_sensor['breakdownindex']>0].drop(['failindex','breakdownindex','FIC552051_718','FI552051_718','PHTIME.552051','WI552051.674'],axis = 1).values
y = df_sensor[df_sensor['breakdownindex']>0].breakdownindex.values

# Define model
reg_all = LinearRegression()

# Split train and test data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.5, random_state=42)

# fit model to train data
reg_all.fit(X_train,y_train)

# Predict on the test data: y_pred
y_pred = reg_all.predict(X_test)

# Compute and print R^2 and RMSE
print("R^2: {}".format(reg_all.score(X_train, y_train)))
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,y_pred))
print("Root Mean Squared Error: {}".format(rmse))


plt.figure(figsize=(20,15))

for i in range(17):
    plt.subplot(4, 5, i+1)
    # predict breakdown index for each fail interval with the model
    X = df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].drop(['failindex','breakdownindex','FIC552051_718','FI552051_718','PHTIME.552051','WI552051.674'],axis = 1).values
    y = df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].breakdownindex.values
    y_pred = reg_all.predict(X)
    
    # plot predicted breakdown index
    plt.plot(df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].index,y_pred)
    plt.title(str(i)+': '+df_fail.iloc[i+1,3])
    plt.ylabel('breakdown index')

## Conclusion of the first modelling approach
Overall, the model did not perform very well. The R^2 coefficient indicates that most of the data don't follow the linear model well. However, looking at the individual interval predictions above, in some cases the predicted failure index follows a linear trend towards 1 (e.g. #12 and #14). Interestingly, there are even some with a negative trend (e.g. #15). But in general, the model is not suitable to be used as a general model to predict machine failure.
One reason why this general model did not work to predict all fail events equally, might be that machine failure is not caused always by the same technical event. For example, a leakage in a vacuum system leads to different sensory events (e.g. pressure change) than failure of electric components (e.g. voltage change). As a result, each fail event might be accompanied by different sensory events. To further investigate this problem, we will now test if each failing event is unique or whether some failing events fall into categories of events.

## Modelling applied to each time interval
In order to compare the individual failing events, we now calculate an individual model for each fail interval. For each calculated model, we then extract the regression coefficients. The idea is that these coefficients are then indicative for a certain failure type. Following the imaginative example from before, all vacuum leakage failures might be described with a high regression coefficient for a pressure sensure variable.

# We define a new array, coef_collection, that will contain all linear regression coefficiets
coef_collection = np.zeros([17,105])
plt.figure(figsize=(20,15))

# Then for each fail interval, we will calculate an own linear regression model and plot the predicted coefficients
for i in range(17):
    plt.subplot(4, 5, i+1)
    
    X = df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].drop(['failindex','breakdownindex','FIC552051_718','FI552051_718','PHTIME.552051','WI552051.674'],axis = 1).values
    y = df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].breakdownindex.values
    
    #X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.1, random_state=42)

    # Create the regressor: reg_all
    reg_all = LinearRegression()

    # Fit the regressor to the training data
    reg_all.fit(X,y)

    # Predict on the test data: y_pred
    y_pred = reg_all.predict(X)
    
    coef_collection[i,:] = reg_all.coef_
  
    plt.plot(df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].index,y_pred)
    plt.title(str(i)+': '+df_fail.iloc[i+1,3])
    plt.ylabel('breakdown index')

Each fail event now follows well a linear trend towards 1. Some models are more variable (e.g. 2), whereas some are very close to a straight line (e.g. 3).

## Comparing correlation coefficients of different models
With the new collection of regression coefficients, coef_collection, we now investigate if some models are similiar to each other. This can be done by calculating a correlation Matrix.

# calculating the correlation matrix
C = np.corrcoef(coef_collection)

# plot the matrix. Positive correlation blue, negative correlation red
plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
plt.imshow(C, cmap="seismic_r")
plt.colorbar()

We can see that there is some diversity in the different models, because the individual model coefficients correlate different with each other. However, some models are closer together (high correlation) compared to others. For example, model 0 and model 1 have a high correlation and might describe similiar events.

# Correlation network
In order to better visualize coefficients of similiar models, we create a network that only keeps models with a high correlation coefficient together (>0.5)

# Format correlation matrix into list of interacting variables
corr = pd.DataFrame(C)
links = corr.stack().reset_index()
links.columns = ['var1', 'var2','value']
links_filtered=links.loc[ (abs(links['value']) > 0.5) & (links['var1'] != links['var2']) ]

# Build hte graph
G = nx.from_pandas_edgelist(links_filtered, 'var1', 'var2')

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
# plot Graph
nx.draw(G, with_labels=True,node_size=1000,font_size=15)

With this parameters, it looks like there are 3 different model types that have similiar regression coefficients. For example, models 5 6 and 14 represent one such a similiar cluster.

# Build new model based on individual similiar clusters
We are now using this information to build a new model, that might take into account individual failure types. For this, we calulate the model based on only the intervals that were shown to have similiar regeression coefficients in the individual analyis (See above).

# We select the fail indices for the cluster at the top
numformodel = [5,6,14]

# we create a boolean index to access these 3 intervals
whichselect = []
for i in numformodel:
    whichselect.append(df_sensor['failindex']==i+1)
   
whichselect = np.any(whichselect,axis =0)
sum(whichselect)

# Select of the data from boolean index 
X = df_sensor[whichselect].drop(['failindex','breakdownindex','FIC552051_718','FI552051_718','PHTIME.552051','WI552051.674'],axis = 1).values
y = df_sensor[whichselect].breakdownindex.values    

# fit model
reg_all = LinearRegression()

# Split data into test, train
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.5, random_state=42)



# Fit the regressor to the training data
reg_all.fit(X_train,y_train)

# Predict test data
y_pred = reg_all.predict(X_test)

# calculate model characteristics
print("R^2: {}".format(reg_all.score(X_train, y_train)))
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,y_pred))
print("Root Mean Squared Error: {}".format(rmse))


plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))


for i in numformodel:
    plt.subplot(4, 5, i+1)
    X = df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].drop(['failindex','breakdownindex','FIC552051_718','FI552051_718','PHTIME.552051','WI552051.674'],axis = 1).values
    y = df_sensor[df_sensor['failindex']==i+1].breakdownindex.values
    y_pred = reg_all.predict(X)
    
    coef_collection[i,:] = reg_all.coef_
    linearfit = np.polyfit(range(len(y)), y, 1)
    plt.plot(range(len(y_pred)),y_pred)
    plt.plot(range(len(y_pred)),range(len(y_pred))*linearfit[0]+linearfit[1])
    
    plt.title(str(i)+': '+df_fail.iloc[i+1,3])
    plt.ylabel('breakdown index')

The R^2 value is much better now (0.71 compared to 0.33 with the general model). When we predict only the 3 intervals, we get a linear response for all of the intervals. Interestingly, all 3 intervals fall into the same error description "CENTRIFUGE - HORIZONTAL".

# Explaining error with most discriminant coefficients
As stated above, with the linear regression model we can quickly retrieve the regression coefficients that contribute most to the model (And therefore the sensor parameters that contribute most to the failure propagation).

# Transform coefficients to pandas DataFrame
coefficients = pd.DataFrame(reg_all.coef_,columns = ['Regression Coefficient Value'])
coefficients['sensorname'] = df_sensor.columns.drop(['failindex','breakdownindex','FIC552051_718','FI552051_718','PHTIME.552051','WI552051.674']).values
coefficients.set_index('sensorname', inplace=True)
# sort values according to coefficient value
coefficients = coefficients.sort_values('Regression Coefficient Value')

# Display top 5 positive and negative coefficients
print(coefficients[0:5],coefficients[-5:])

Without knowing anything about the sensors, it looks like the sensors "VI552051.748" and "SI552051.801" seem to be important for the progression of the discussed failure events (They are among the top 2 positive and top 2 negative sensors).

## Conclusion and Outlook
We demonstrate that the underlying sensor data might not be modeled using a generalized model over all failure events, at least not with the modeling method chosen here. However, with our approach we could identify 3 event classes that might be used for individual model selection. With this approach, we could also identify key sensor variables which contribute to one such an individual event.

Ideas for further progress
- For the moment, maintenance on the instrument is done by fixed time schedule (preventive maintenance). As for this data, there are only the failing events listed and not preventive maintenance. It is to expect that preventive maintenance might affect the proposed model used here, as the "health state" of the machines might go back to normal after such visits. It would be interesting to include this effect
- The failure propagation might not follow at all a linear trend, so different models should be tested
- Only one of the 3 "cluster" models was further investigated. What about the other 2?
